   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(10,10))\n",
    "Nrows, Ncols = image.shape\n",
    "im  = ax.imshow(image, cmap=plt.get_cmap('turbo'), interpolation=\"nearest\", origin='lower', extent=[0,Nrows,0,Ncols])\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"x pixel number $N_x$ [px]\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"y pixel number $N_y$ [px]\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The noisy image above shows a part of a lattice structure. The structure consists of 4 identical atoms (faint) on the vertices of a (rotated) square, with an atom of another species (pronounced) in the middle of the square. The structure is embedded in a constant background. You can assume that each of the atoms can be modeled with a spherically-symmetric Gaussian function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Your tasks for this exercise are the following:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Perform a non-linear least-squares fit to determine the heights, the (x,y) positions (pixels), and the standard deviations [pixels] of the Gaussian functions, taking into account the constraints of the lattice. Visualize your solution.\n",
    "- Demonstrate that a model with 5 Gaussians fits the image indeed better than a model with just one Gaussian, despite the extra number of fit parameters.  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Tip:** if you want to use a regression library that expects 1D arrays instead of the 2D array like the image above, you can use the ravel() function in NumPy to convert the image in a long 1D array. For example:\n",
    "\n",
    "`image.ravel()`\n",
    "\n",
    "returns the entire image in a 1D array. The corresponding pixel coordinates can be obtained in a long 1D array with \n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "N=100\n",
    "x = np.arange(N)\n",
    "y = np.arange(N)\n",
    "Xpix, Ypix = np.meshgrid(x, y)\n",
    "X = Xpix.ravel()\n",
    "Y = Ypix.ravel()\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Before fitting, we inspect the image numerically to inform our initial \n",
    "parameter guesses. The mean intensity serves as the background estimate, \n",
    "the maximum intensity indicates the peak of the center atom, and the \n",
    "image shape tells us the number of data points."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "print(f\"Image shape: {image.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Min intensity: {image.min():.1f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Max intensity: {image.max():.1f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Mean intensity: {image.mean():.1f}\")"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We locate the pixel coordinates of the maximum intensity to use as the \n",
    "initial guess for the center atom position $(x_c, y_c)$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#finding the peak position\n",
    "peak_idx = np.unravel_index(np.argmax(image), image.shape)\n",
    "print(f\"Peak at row={peak_idx[0]}, col={peak_idx[1]}\")"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "`curve_fit` expects 1D input arrays, but the image is a 2D array. We \n",
    "therefore create a grid of pixel coordinates (X, Y) and flatten both \n",
    "the coordinates and the image intensities to 1D using `ravel()`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "N = 100\n",
    "x = np.arange(N)\n",
    "y = np.arange(N)\n",
    "Xpix, Ypix = np.meshgrid(x, y)\n",
    "X = Xpix.ravel()\n",
    "Y = Ypix.ravel()\n",
    "\n",
    "XY = (X, Y)\n",
    "Z = image.ravel()"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The image is modeled as a sum of 5 spherically symmetric gaussians on a constant background. \n",
    "The 4 corner atoms are assumed to share the same height and width \n",
    "since they are identical atoms of the same species. Rather than fitting 4 independent positions, we exploit \n",
    "the known crystal structure by parameterizing the corners as a rotated \n",
    "square with center $(c_x, c_y)$, half-diagonal $r$, and rotation angle \n",
    "$\\phi$, reducing the number of free parameters from 8 to 3. \n",
    "The full model has 11 free parameters."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#model the function\n",
    "def model_5gaussians(XY, \n",
    "                     B,                          # background\n",
    "                     A_c, x_c, y_c, sig_c,       # center atom\n",
    "                     A_f, sig_f,                  # corner atoms (shared A and sigma)\n",
    "                     cx, cy, r, phi):             # square geometry\n",
    "\n",
    "    X, Y = XY  # unpack pixel coordinates\n",
    "\n",
    "    # compute 4 corner positions\n",
    "    angles = np.deg2rad(np.array([45, 135, 225, 315]) + phi)\n",
    "    x_corners = cx + r * np.cos(angles)\n",
    "    y_corners = cy + r * np.sin(angles)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # center atom Gaussian\n",
    "    Z = B + A_c * np.exp(-((X - x_c)**2 + (Y - y_c)**2) / (2 * sig_c**2))\n",
    "\n",
    "    # add 4 corner atom Gaussians\n",
    "    for x0, y0 in zip(x_corners, y_corners):\n",
    "        Z += A_f * np.exp(-((X - x0)**2 + (Y - y0)**2) / (2 * sig_f**2))\n",
    "\n",
    "    return Z.ravel()"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Initial guesses for all 11 parameters are derived from the image \n",
    "statistics computed earlier. The background $B$ is set to the mean \n",
    "intensity, and $(x_c, y_c)$ to the coordinates of the peak pixel. \n",
    "The center atom width $\\sigma_c$ is guessed as ~4 px, consistent \n",
    "with a blob a few pixels wide. The corner atom amplitude $A_f$ is \n",
    "set to 40 intensity units above background, reflecting their faint \n",
    "appearance. The half-diagonal $r$ is estimated as 20 px from visual \n",
    "inspection, and $\\phi = 0$ since no prior information on the rotation \n",
    "is available. These guesses need not be exact, only close enough for \n",
    "the optimizer to converge."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#initial guesses\n",
    "B     = 1014   # background\n",
    "A_c   = 164    # center atom height above background\n",
    "x_c   = 54     # center atom x position (col)\n",
    "y_c   = 60     # center atom y position (row)\n",
    "sig_c = 4      # center atom width (guess)\n",
    "A_f   = 40     # corner atom height above background (guess)\n",
    "sig_f = 4      # corner atom width (guess)\n",
    "cx    = 54     # square center x (same as center atom)\n",
    "cy    = 60     # square center y (same as center atom)\n",
    "r     = 20     # half-diagonal of square (guess)\n",
    "phi   = 0      # rotation angle (guess)\n",
    "\n",
    "p0 = [B, A_c, x_c, y_c, sig_c, A_f, sig_f, cx, cy, r, phi]"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We fit the model to the image using nonlinear least squares, which minimizes the sum of squared residuals to find the best-fit parameters"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "from scipy.optimize import curve_fit\n",
    "\n",
    "popt, pcov = curve_fit(model_5gaussians, XY, Z, p0=p0)"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Parameter uncertainties are extracted from the covariance matrix `pcov` \n",
    "returned by `curve_fit`, using `correlated_values` which accounts for \n",
    "correlations between parameters."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "from uncertainties import correlated_values\n",
    "\n",
    "params = correlated_values(popt, pcov)\n",
    "param_names = ['B', 'A_c', 'x_c', 'y_c', 'sig_c', 'A_f', 'sig_f', 'cx', 'cy', 'r', 'phi']\n",
    "\n",
    "for name, param in zip(param_names, params):\n",
    "    print(f\"{name:8s} = {param}\")"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We visualize the original image, the fitted model, and the residuals \n",
    "(data minus fit). A good fit is indicated by the fitted model \n",
    "reproducing the structure of the original image, and residuals showing \n",
    "no systematic structure."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Z_fit = model_5gaussians(XY, *popt).reshape(100, 100)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(18, 6))\n",
    "\n",
    "vmin = image.min()\n",
    "vmax = image.max()\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].imshow(image, cmap='turbo', origin='lower', \n",
    "               extent=[0,100,0,100], vmin=vmin, vmax=vmax)\n",
    "axes[0].set_title('Original image')\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel('x [px]')\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel('y [px]')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].imshow(Z_fit, cmap='turbo', origin='lower', \n",
    "               extent=[0,100,0,100], vmin=vmin, vmax=vmax)\n",
    "axes[1].set_title('Fitted model')\n",
    "axes[1].set_xlabel('x [px]')\n",
    "axes[1].set_ylabel('y [px]')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[2].imshow(image - Z_fit, cmap='RdBu', origin='lower', extent=[0,100,0,100])\n",
    "axes[2].set_title('Residuals (data - fit)')\n",
    "axes[2].set_xlabel('x [px]')\n",
    "axes[2].set_ylabel('y [px]')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To verify that ordinary least squares is justified, we inspect the \n",
    "distribution of the residuals. If the noise is Gaussian, the residual \n",
    "histogram should follow a normal distribution centered on zero."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "from scipy.stats import norm\n",
    "residuals = image.ravel() - Z_fit.ravel()\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,5))\n",
    "ax.hist(residuals, bins=50, edgecolor = 'black', \n",
    "       density=True, label=\"Resiudals\")\n",
    "\n",
    "#fit gaussian to the residuals and overlay it\n",
    "mu, std = norm.fit(residuals)\n",
    "x_range = np.linspace(residuals.min(), residuals.max(), 200)\n",
    "ax.plot(x_range, norm.pdf(x_range, mu, std), 'r-', lw=2, label=f'Normal fit (μ={mu:.1f}, σ={std:.1f})')\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"residual intensity\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"probability density\")\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Residual Histogram\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To compare models, we first compute the residual sum of squares (RSS) \n",
    "for the 5-Gaussian fit, which serves as an ingredient for the AIC and BIC."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "RSS_5g = np.sum(residuals**2)\n",
    "print(f\"RSS (5 Gaussians) = {RSS_5g:.2f}\")"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As a baseline for comparison, we fit a simpler model with just one \n",
    "Gaussian on a constant background. Demonstrating that the 5-Gaussian \n",
    "model is better requires a reference to compare against."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "def model_1gaussian(XY, B, A_c, x_c, y_c, sig_c):\n",
    "    X, Y = XY\n",
    "    Z = B + A_c * np.exp(-((X - x_c)**2 + (Y - y_c)**2) / (2 * sig_c**2))\n",
    "    return Z.ravel()"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "p0_1g = [1014, 164, 54, 60, 4]\n",
    "\n",
    "popt_1g, pcov_1g = curve_fit(model_1gaussian, XY, Z, p0=p0_1g)"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Z_fit_1g = model_1gaussian(XY, *popt_1g).reshape(100, 100)\n",
    "residuals_1g = image.ravel() - Z_fit_1g.ravel()\n",
    "RSS_1g = np.sum(residuals_1g**2)"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We compute AIC and BIC for both models. Both criteria penalize model \n",
    "complexity but by different amounts, BIC penalizes extra parameters \n",
    "more harshly than AIC for large datasets. A lower value indicates a \n",
    "better balance between fit quality and model complexity."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "n = 100 * 100  # number of data points\n",
    "\n",
    "k_5g = 11  # parameters in 5-Gaussian model\n",
    "k_1g = 5   # parameters in 1-Gaussian model\n",
    "\n",
    "# log-likelihood approximation\n",
    "logL_5g = -n/2 * np.log(RSS_5g / n)\n",
    "logL_1g = -n/2 * np.log(RSS_1g / n)\n",
    "\n",
    "# AIC\n",
    "AIC_5g = 2*k_5g - 2*logL_5g\n",
    "AIC_1g = 2*k_1g - 2*logL_1g\n",
    "\n",
    "# BIC\n",
    "BIC_5g = k_5g*np.log(n) - 2*logL_5g\n",
    "BIC_1g = k_1g*np.log(n) - 2*logL_1g\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"{'Model':<15} {'k':>4} {'RSS':>14} {'AIC':>12} {'BIC':>12}\")\n",
    "print(f\"{'1 Gaussian':<15} {k_1g:>4} {RSS_1g:>14.2f} {AIC_1g:>12.2f} {BIC_1g:>12.2f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"{'5 Gaussians':<15} {k_5g:>4} {RSS_5g:>14.2f} {AIC_5g:>12.2f} {BIC_5g:>12.2f}\")"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Conclusion\n",
    "We performed a nonlinear least-squares fit of 5 Gaussians to the TEM \n",
    "image, successfully locating the center atom at $(x_c, y_c) = (56.2 \n",
    "\\pm 0.2, 55.9 \\pm 0.2)$ px and the 4 corner atoms arranged in a \n",
    "rotated square with half-diagonal $r = 25.0 \\pm 0.4$ px and rotation \n",
    "angle $\\phi = -27.4 \\pm 0.8$ degrees. The fit is supported by the \n",
    "residual image showing no systematic structure and a residual histogram \n",
    "consistent with a normal distribution. Model comparison via AIC and BIC \n",
    "confirms that the 5-Gaussian model is strongly preferred over a simpler \n",
    "1-Gaussian model ($\\Delta$AIC = 264, $\\Delta$BIC = 221, both well above \n",
    "the threshold of 10), demonstrating that all 5 atoms are genuine \n",
    "features in the image."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Task 2: Elliptical galaxies"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Elliptical galaxies are galaxies that have an ellipsoidal shape and a smooth featureless appearance. A famous example is the galaxy NGC4472 also known as M49, which is located in the constellation of Virgo, about 56 million lightyears away from us. The galaxy is believed to host a massive black hole of more than 500 million solar masses. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "Image(url=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JorisDeRidder/DataAnalysisInPhysicsAndAstronomy/main/Images/M49.jpeg\", width=700)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The image above shows the elliptical galaxy NGC4472. Credit: David W. Hogg, Michael R. Blanton, and the Sloan Digital Sky Survey Collaboration."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "NGC4472 is part of a cluster of galaxies called the Virgo cluster, which contains more than 1300 galaxies:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "Image(url=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JorisDeRidder/DataAnalysisInPhysicsAndAstronomy/main/Images/Virgo_cluster.png\", width=700)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The image above shows the Virgo cluster, which was edited so that no foreground stars are visible. Credit: Pablo Carlos Budassi."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As the image of NGC4472 clearly shows, the local surface intensity $I$ of the galaxy clearly decreases from the core to the edge of the galaxy. One of the first attempts to model this behavior was the intensity profile proposed by Hubble in 1930):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ I(r) = I_0 \\ (1 + r/r_e)^{-2} $$\n",
    "\n",
    "Here $I(r)$ is the intensity as a function of angular distance $r$, and $I_0$ and $r_e$ are free (fit) parameters. Another model was proposed by Vaucouleurs in 1948:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ I(r) = I_0 \\ e^{-k [(r/r_e)^{1/4} - 1]} $$\n",
    "\n",
    "with $k=7.669$, and yet another profile by Sérsic (1968):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ I(r) = I_0 \\ 10^{-b_n [(r/r_e)^{1/n} -1]} $$\n",
    "\n",
    "The parameter $r_e$ and in the case of Sérsic's profile also the (real-valued) parameter $n$ can be linked to the structure of the galaxy. In Sérsic's law, $b_n = 0.868 n - 0.142$ for $n\\in[0.5, 16.5]$.  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The datasets for this exercise are borrowed from Feigelson & Babu (2012) who in turn extracted it from Kormendy et al. (2009). They contain the observed surface brightness profile of three elliptical galaxies: NGC4472, NGC4551, NGC4406. In practice, not the intensity $I(r)$ itself can be measured, but the surface brightness\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\mu(r) = \\mu_0 - 2.5 \\log_{10} I(r) $$\n",
    "\n",
    "which is expressed in magnitude per square arcsec. The exact unit is not really relevant for this exercise."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "url = \"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JorisDeRidder/DataAnalysisInPhysicsAndAstronomy/main/Datasets/NGC4472_profile.csv\"\n",
    "ngc4472 = pd.read_csv(url)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "url = \"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JorisDeRidder/DataAnalysisInPhysicsAndAstronomy/main/Datasets/NGC4551_profile.csv\"\n",
    "ngc4551 = pd.read_csv(url)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "url = \"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JorisDeRidder/DataAnalysisInPhysicsAndAstronomy/main/Datasets/NGC4406_profile.csv\"\n",
    "ngc4406 = pd.read_csv(url)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ngc4472.head()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The columns in the datasets are:\n",
    "- **radius**: the radial distance $r$ on the sky from the core of the galaxy [arcsec]\n",
    "- **surf_mag**: the surface brightness $\\mu(r)$ of the galaxy  [mag/arcsec$^2$]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The parameter $\\mu_0=26$ for NGC4472 and NGC4451, and $\\mu_0= 32$ for NGC4406. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Your tasks for this exercise are the following:\n",
    "- Fit the three models mentioned above to these three galaxy datasets. The relevant fit parameters are $I_0$, $r_e$ and $n$.\n",
    "- Use both the Akaike as well as the Bayesian information criterion to determine which model should be preferred. Quantify how much you prefer one model above the other. Compare the two approaches.\n",
    "- Diagnose your regression, and verify whether using ordinary non-linear least-squares is indeed justified. If you see something \"anomalous\" can you speculate what the reason could be?\n",
    "- Determine $2\\sigma$ individual confidence intervals for the parameters $r_e$ and $n$.\n",
    "- For NGC4472, determine a $2\\sigma$ joint confidence interval of $r_e$ and $n$ and visualize it on a plot together with contours of the cost function $S(\\mathbf{\\theta})$.\n",
    "- Again for NGC4472, use bootstrapping to determine individual confidence intervals for the parameters $r_e$ and $n$. Think about the best bootstrap sampling method."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Mu1 = 26\n",
    "Mu2 = 26\n",
    "Mu3 = 32\n",
    "I1 = 10**((Mu1-ngc4472['surf_mag'])/2.5)\n",
    "r1 = ngc4472['radius']\n",
    "I2 = 10**((Mu2-ngc4551['surf_mag'])/2.5)\n",
    "r2 = ngc4551['radius']\n",
    "I3 = 10**((Mu3-ngc4406['surf_mag'])/2.5)\n",
    "r3 = ngc4406['radius']"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,3, figsize=(18,8))\n",
    "ax[0].scatter(r1, I1, c=\"red\", marker='o', s=50, label=\"ngc4472\")\n",
    "ax[1].scatter(r2, I2, c=\"blue\", marker='^', s=30, label=\"ngc4551\")\n",
    "ax[2].scatter(r3, I3, c=\"green\", marker='v', s=30, label=\"ngc4406\")\n",
    "ax[0].set_xlabel('r[arcsec]')\n",
    "ax[0].set_ylabel('I[unitless]')\n",
    "ax[0].legend(loc=1)\n",
    "ax[1].set_xlabel('r[arcsec]')\n",
    "ax[1].set_ylabel('I[unitless]')\n",
    "ax[1].legend(loc=1)\n",
    "ax[2].set_xlabel('r[arcsec]')\n",
    "ax[2].set_xlabel('r[arcsec]')\n",
    "ax[2].set_ylabel('I[unitless]')\n",
    "ax[2].legend(loc=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "k=7.669\n",
    "def func1(r, I_0, r_e):\n",
    "    I = I_0 * (1 + r/r_e)**(-2)\n",
    "    return I\n",
    "def func2(r, I_0, r_e):\n",
    "    I = I_0 * np.exp(-k*((r/r_e)**(1/4)-1))\n",
    "    return I\n",
    "def func3(r, I_0, r_e, n):\n",
    "    b = 0.868*n-0.142\n",
    "    I = I_0 * np.exp(-b*((r/r_e)**(1/n)-1))\n",
    "    return I\n"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "myModel1 = lmfit.Model(func1)\n",
    "myModel2 = lmfit.Model(func2)\n",
    "myModel3 = lmfit.Model(func3)"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "myModel1.set_param_hint('I_0', value=10000, min=0.0)\n",
    "myModel1.set_param_hint('r_e', value=100, min=0.0)\n",
    "myModel2.set_param_hint('I_0', value=10000, min=0.0)\n",
    "myModel2.set_param_hint('r_e', value=100, min=0.0)\n",
    "myModel3.set_param_hint('I_0', value=10000, min=0.0)\n",
    "myModel3.set_param_hint('r_e', value=100, min=0.0)\n",
    "myModel3.set_param_hint('n', value=16.5, min=0.5)"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "myFit11 = myModel1.fit(I1, r=r1)\n",
    "myFit12 = myModel1.fit(I2, r=r2)\n",
    "myFit13 = myModel1.fit(I3, r=r3)\n",
    "myFit21 = myModel2.fit(I1, r=r1)\n",
    "myFit22 = myModel2.fit(I2, r=r2)\n",
    "myFit23 = myModel2.fit(I3, r=r3)\n",
    "myFit31 = myModel3.fit(I1, r=r1)\n",
    "myFit32 = myModel3.fit(I2, r=r2)\n",
    "myFit33 = myModel3.fit(I3, r=r3)"
   ],
   "outputs": [],
   "execution_count": null
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "AIC1 = np.array([myFit11.aic, myFit21.aic, myFit31.aic])\n",
    "AIC2 = np.array([myFit12.aic, myFit22.aic, myFit32.aic])\n",
    "AIC3 = np.array([myFit13.aic, myFit23.aic, myFit33.aic])\n",
    "BIC1 = np.array([myFit11.bic, myFit21.bic, myFit31.bic])\n",
