   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(10,8))\n",
    "ax.errorbar(data['z'], data['mu'], yerr=data['sigma'], fmt='o')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('redshift z')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('distance modulus $\\mu$') \n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It would be very useful to have an empirical relation that can be used to predict the distance (or distance modulus) of the supernova given the easily measurable redshift. One possible option is to simply fit a polynomial model\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\mu(z_n) = \\theta_0 + \\sum_{k=1}^K \\theta_k \\ z_n^k + \\varepsilon_n $\n",
    "\n",
    "to the data, and use this model to predict the distance modulus for future supernovae. This will **not** be done in this exercise. Instead of using $x^k$ as base functions, we will be using gaussian base functions:\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\mu(z_n) = \\theta_0 + \\sum_{k=1}^K \\theta_k e^{-\\frac{(z_n - x_k)^2}{2 h^2}} + \\varepsilon_n $\n",
    "\n",
    "This type of regression is called a *gaussian basis function regression*. Here $(z_n, \\mu_n=\\mu(z_n))$ are the observations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Your tasks are:\n",
    "- Fit a model with $K=100$ gaussian basis functions, each with a standard deviation $h=0.14$, and a mean $x_k$ given by the dense grid `x = np.linspace(0.05, 1.85, K)`. \n",
    "- Visualize your fit, and plot the fit coefficients $\\theta_k$ as a function of $k \\in \\{1,..,K\\}$. Explain what you see.\n",
    "- Redo the fit with the same model using Ridge and Lasso regression, where you determine in both cases the regularization parameter $\\lambda$ using 10-fold cross-validation. \n",
    "- Visualize the Ridge and the Lasso fits, and plot again the fit coefficients. Compare their magnitude with the regular fit coefficients."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Another alternative to create an empirical is **kernel regression**, sometimes also called **Nadaraya-Watson regression**. Kernel regression is a non-parametric approach, that does not involve fitting model parameters. As a kernel we will choose a Gaussian kernel, which leads to the following model:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ \\mu(z_{\\rm new}) = \\frac{\\displaystyle\\sum_{n=1}^N \\mu_n e^{-\\frac{(z_{\\rm new} - z_n)^2}{2 h^2}}}{\\sum_{n=1}^N e^{-\\frac{(z_{\\rm new} - z_n)^2}{2 h^2}} } $$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $(z_n, \\mu_n)$ are the observed data. As you can see, this model estimates the distance modulus $\\mu$ at an arbitrary value $z_{\\rm new}$ by computing a weighted average over all observed $\\mu_n$ values. Those $\\mu_n$ values that have a corresponding $z_n$ value closer to the requested $z_{\\rm new}$ value get a larger weight.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Compute and plot an empirical relationship between $\\mu$ and $z$ using gaussian kernel regression, where you determine an optimal value for $h$ using 10-fold cross-validation. For visualization you can use $z_{\\rm new}$ = `np.linspace(0.05, 1.85, 100)`. Compare your result with the one obtained with regularized regression."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 72,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "z = data['z'].values\n",
    "mu = data['mu'].values\n",
    "sigma = data['sigma'].values\n",
    "\n",
    "# Gaussian basis function parameters\n",
    "K = 100\n",
    "h = 0.14\n",
    "x_k = np.linspace(0.05, 1.85, K)  # centers of the K bumps\n",
    "\n",
    "# Build design matrix: shape (N, K+1)\n",
    "# Column 0: the intercept (theta_0), all ones\n",
    "# Columns 1..K: the K Gaussian bumps evaluated at each z_n\n",
    "N = len(z)\n",
    "Phi = np.zeros((N, K + 1))\n",
    "Phi[:, 0] = 1.0  # intercept column\n",
    "\n",
    "for k in range(K):\n",
    "    Phi[:, k + 1] = np.exp(-((z - x_k[k])**2) / (2 * h**2))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 73,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#WLS fit\n",
    "weights = 1.0 / sigma**2\n",
    "wls_model = sm.WLS(mu, Phi, weights=weights)\n",
    "result = wls_model.fit()\n",
    "\n",
    "theta = result.params  # shape (K+1,): theta_0 then theta_1..theta_K"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 74,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Predict on a fine grid for smooth curve\n",
    "z_grid = np.linspace(0.05, 1.85, 500)\n",
    "Phi_grid = np.zeros((500, K + 1))\n",
    "Phi_grid[:, 0] = 1.0\n",
    "for k in range(K):\n",
    "    Phi_grid[:, k + 1] = np.exp(-((z_grid - x_k[k])**2) / (2 * h**2))\n",
    "\n",
    "mu_pred = Phi_grid @ theta\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot 1: data + fit\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "ax.errorbar(z, mu, yerr=sigma, fmt='o', label='Data', alpha=0.6)\n",
    "ax.plot(z_grid, mu_pred, color='red', label='Gaussian basis fit')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Redshift z')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Distance modulus μ [mag]')\n",
    "ax.set_title('Gaussian basis function regression (K=100, h=0.14)')\n",
    "ax.legend()\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot 2: coefficients theta_1 .. theta_K\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))\n",
    "ax.plot(np.arange(1, K + 1), theta[1:], marker='o', markersize=3)\n",
    "ax.axhline(0, color='gray', linestyle='--')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('k')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('θ_k')\n",
    "ax.set_title('Fit coefficients θ_k (k = 1 ... K)')\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
